{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}
{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}
The '''Roundabout Appreciation Society''' ('''UKRAS''') is a group of people in the [[United Kingdom]] that discuss [[traffic]] [[roundabout]]s. The main topic of discussion is the [[architecture]] of the roundabouts, including their design and safety features. Other topics have included the approaches people take when driving towards and around a roundabout, and the [[wildlife]] present on some of the larger junctions. Their aim is to promote safe driving and consideration towards other road users.

The society was formed by Kevin Beresford after the success of a [[wall calendar|calendar]] that showed photographs of 12 roundabouts in [[Redditch]] &ndash; it sold 100,000 worldwide. As of 2013, the association is reportedly trying to attract more women members, by putting a windmill on the front cover of its calendar.<ref>{{cite news|title=Roundabout Society 'sex-up' 2013 cult calendar by putting a windmill on the front cover|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/features/4594256/roundabout-society-sex-up-calendar-windmill-on-front.html|accessdate=30 January 2013|newspaper=The Sun|date=17 October 2012}}</ref>

